Revival of the Great Leader
London — The Battle of Waterloo has long since passed, and Napoleon's catastrophic defeat in that battle severely damaged France's self-respect, to the extent that General de Gaulle omitted any mention of the battle when writing the history of the French military.
Nevertheless, if you admit that "greatness" is a personal quality, then both Napoleon and de Gaulle could be considered the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there is absolutely no such thing as a "great leader."
In Marx's view, the class struggle in France created an environment in which a "strange mediocrity" like Napoleon could become a hero.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon was not particularly outstanding as a general; his victories were due to the courage and devotion of the French soldiers who won the Battle of Borodino.
Whether Napoleon was great or not, we must clarify whether "greatness" can be used to describe any leader.
If the answer is affirmative, then who can be described as great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believed that great leaders must meet two particularly important criteria.
First, can this leader recognize the historical trend?
Otto von Bismarck did so, as did his German compatriot Konrad Adenauer; using Bismarck's memorable words, both heard the "rustling of God's cloak."
Secondly, did this leader make an important decision?
Of course, if a leader is forced to make a decision, he or she cannot be blamed for it nor can they take credit for it.
Therefore, the key lies in whether leaders have the opportunity to weigh the pros and cons and make the correct decisions on behalf of the nation.
De Gaulle should therefore certainly be on any list of great leaders.
Almost single-handedly, he led France out of the relegation zone after World War II.
After regaining power in 1958, he saved his country once again by crushing two attempted coups, ending the Algerian War, and drafting the Constitution of the Fifth Republic.
Like British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview, establishing their place in the postwar global order.
In fact, the ultimate impact of de Gaulle and Churchill in shaping their respective worldviews was somewhat excessive.
Their successors would for years continue to view the world—and the role their own country played—in ways that constrained rational inquiry and distorted decision-making.
As a result, the leaders that came after the two countries were never able to achieve accomplishments that could match those of the two great leaders.
But there is another British prime minister who can match him: she is Margaret Thatcher, a highly controversial figure, loved by as many people as she is disliked.
Even her resignation 25 years ago was due to resistance activities within her own cabinet and party.
But you don't need to please everyone to become a great leader.
In fact, even Thatcher's critics could not deny her influence.
In addition to becoming the first woman Prime Minister of the United Kingdom and one of the earliest female Prime Ministers in other countries, Thatcher helped reverse the UK's economic decline.
Moreover, her attacks on overly powerful unions enhanced their manageability during a time when the nation seemed to be sliding into chaos and turmoil.
Given this, she undoubtedly has the right to be a candidate for the "Great Leader."
Similarly, although far from perfect, Deng Xiaoping of China also qualifies as a great leader.
In addition to assisting Mao Zedong in committing evil deeds, Deng played a decisive role in ordering the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre.
But Deng also revitalized the market, leading China onto an unprecedented path of development and prosperity that ultimately lifted hundreds of millions of Chinese out of poverty.
Many people consider Lee Kuan Yew, the founder of Singapore and its long-serving prime minister, to be great, although he might have wished to showcase his talents on a bigger stage.
In fact, the size of a country does not seem to affect a person's ability to become a great leader.
I made no derogatory remarks when I said that a small country like Luxembourg is unlikely to produce great leaders, especially since the political climate in the country is generally not very contentious.
The United States is vast enough to serve as the birthplace of great leaders.
Some presidents have indeed achieved a great deal.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower — though not exactly intellectual giants — demonstrated remarkable judgment in establishing the postwar international order that sustained world peace for decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possess extraordinary talents — the ability to motivate and the art of persuasion.
John F. Kennedy was a man of many talents.
He accomplished a great task: defusing the Cuban Missile Crisis.
His inspiring talent was unparalleled; in fact, his assassination after his death solidified the tradition he left behind.
In South Africa, no one has yet been regarded as a great figure after Nelson Mandela's death, as Mandela embodied courage, authority, and graceful magnanimity.
In fact, he is the most charismatic and fascinating leader I have ever met; the other two — former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former U.S. Secretary of State Colin Powell — are either African or African American.
So what about today?
The only one qualified to claim greatness is the de facto leader of the EU, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at the beginning, but made few mistakes when it came to important decisions.
Kohl formulated generous terms for German unification; Merkel opposed Putin during his invasion of Ukraine and adopted a lenient stance toward the immigration crisis.
I think Marx and Tolstoy were wrong.
Political leaders — the exercisers of political power — can change the situation for better or worse.
Merkel is the most obvious example today, as she pointed the way for Europe to tackle its difficult survival crisis.
